</tr>
</table>
</div>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Theorema_Egregium" title="Theorema Egregium">Theorema Egregium</a> − The "remarkable theorem" discovered by <a href="/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title="Carl Friedrich Gauss">Gauss</a> which showed there is an intrinsic notion of curvature for surfaces. This is used by <a href="/wiki/Riemann" title="Riemann" class="mw-redirect">Riemann</a> to generalize the (intrinsic) notion of curvature to higher dimensional spaces.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/String_Theory#Extra_dimensions" title="String Theory" class="mw-redirect">Extra dimensions in String Theory</a> for 6 or 7 extra space-like dimensions all with a <i>compact</i> topology.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ekpyrotic" title="Ekpyrotic">Ekpyrotic universe</a> − a String theory-related model depicting a <a href="/wiki/Fifth_dimension" title="Fifth dimension">five-dimensional</a>, <a href="/wiki/Membrane_(M-Theory)" title="Membrane (M-Theory)">membrane</a>-shaped universe; an alternative to the <a href="/wiki/Big_Bang" title="Big Bang">Hot Big Bang Model</a>, whereby the universe is described to have originated when two membranes collided at the fifth dimension.</li>
</ul>
<p><a name="References" id="References"></a></p>
